l the story of 2020 anew. It shares reporting from Bowling Green, Virginia; Macon, Georgia; McKeesport, Pennsylvania; and McAllen, Texas—two towns that lost their local newspapers and two where they are barely hanging on. The authors consider what makes each town distinctive and how these local perspectives tell a part of a broader American story. This book reports on how residents of these towns grapple with and talk about issues relating to race, schooling, health, immigration, deindustrialization, as well as local and national politics amid a changing and increasingly precarious information ecosystem. A distinct and intimate look at a calamitous year, American Deadline is an important book for all readers interested in the possibilities and future of local journalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xPress coverage. 0aPress and politicszUnited States. 0aReportage literature, American. 0aRural journalismzUnited States. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh1 aRichardson, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSanchez, Sandra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aShapiro, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShapiro, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/glas2084040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231557412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231557412/original  aEBA_CL_LB  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LB  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK